As an AI, I can certainly provide an example of an intricate style for a marquee in plain text format, but it's important to remember that adding complex styles to deprecated HTML elements such as `<marquee>` is not recommended for a modern web project. In practice, you should use CSS animations to create such effects. However, for the sake of illustration, here's an example of a styled marquee:

```html
<marquee style="
    width: 200px;
    height: 60px;
    scrollamount: 10;
    scrolldelay: 30;
    loop: infinite;
    font-family: 'Courier New', monospace;
    font-size: 24px;
    font-weight: bold;
    color: #FF00FF;
    border: 2px dashed #FFFF00;
    background-color: #0000FF;
    background-image: linear-gradient(to right, rgba(255,0,0,0.5), rgba(0,255,0,0.5), rgba(0,0,255,0.5));
    text-shadow: 2px 2px 4px #000000;
    transform: rotate(5deg) skewX(-20deg);
    box-shadow: 4px 4px 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.5);
    border-radius: 10px;
    overflow: hidden;
    display: block;
    margin: 40px auto;
    text-align: center;
    line-height: 60px;
">
  🚀 Zooming through space! 🌌
</marquee>
```

In this example, various inline styles have been added directly to the `<marquee>` element to make it more visually complex. Some attributes such as `bgcolor`, `hspace`, and `vspace` have been replaced with equivalent CSS properties for better control over the visuals.

Please note that such code is not recommended for use on live websites and should be replaced with standard and accessible techniques provided by modern CSS and JavaScript. If you're considering using a marquee-like effect on a website, research CSS animations or consult frontend frameworks for recommended practices.

It appears you've tried to apply CSS styles to a marquee element. Although the `<marquee>` tag does not support many of these CSS properties through attributes, you can apply these styles inline with the style attribute. However, I must correct the quotes to standard straight quotes, and the `scrollamount`, `scrolldelay`, and `loop` inside the style attribute need to be removed since they are not valid CSS properties. Let me correct that for you:

```html
<marquee behavior="scroll" direction="down" width="50px" height="50px" scrollamount="25" scrolldelay="5" loop="infinite" bgcolor="#000000" hspace="25px" vspace="25px" style="
    width: 200px;
    height: 60px;
    font-family: 'Courier New', monospace;
    font-size: 24px;
    font-weight: bold;
    color: #FF00FF;
    border: 2px dashed #FFFF00;
    background-color: #0000FF;
    background-image: linear-gradient(to right, rgba(255,0,0,0.5), rgba(0,255,0,0.5), rgba(0,0,255,0.5));
    text-shadow: 2px 2px 4px #000000;
    transform: rotate(5deg) skewX(-20deg);
    box-shadow: 4px 4px 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.5);
    border-radius: 10px;
    overflow: hidden;
    display: block;
    margin: 40px auto;
    text-align: center;
    line-height: 60px;
">
  animate
</marquee>
```

Please note that the `width` and `height` styles will override the `width` and `height` attributes of your `<marquee>`. Such code should only be used for educational purposes as the `<marquee>` tag is deprecated and not recommended for production use in modern web development. Instead, consider using CSS animations.

Nested marquees can create unpredictable results as they are not standard HTML practice; additionally, the `<marquee>` element itself is deprecated. However, your provided HTML seems to be an attempt at nesting marquees with opposing directions. Here is the corrected HTML for your two nested marquees:

```html
<br/>
<marquee behavior="alternate" direction="up">
    ~~~
    <marquee behavior="alternate" direction="down">
        ~~~~~~~~~
    </marquee>
    <br/>
    ~~~
</marquee>
<br/>
<marquee behavior="alternate" direction="left">
    ~~~~
    <marquee behavior="alternate" direction="right">
        ~~~~~~~~~
    </marquee>
    <br/>
    ~~~~~
</marquee>
<br/>
```

This will create two sets of marquees:

1. The first set contains an outer marquee that alternates up and down, and an inner marquee that alternates down (likely in opposition to the outer marquee).
2. The second set contains an outer marquee that alternates left and right, and an inner marquee that alternates right (again, likely in opposition to the outer marquee).

Using nested marquees is unusual, and the above code might not work as expected in different browsers due to the non-standard nature of such constructions. It is highly recommended to create such effects using modern web technologies like CSS animations, which provide greater control and cross-browser consistency. Here is an example of how to achieve an alternating effect with CSS:

```html
<div class="marquee-container">
    <div class="marquee vertical">
        ~~~
        <div class="marquee vertical inner">
            ~~~~~~~~~
        </div>
        <br/>
        ~~~
    </div>
    <div class="marquee horizontal">
        ~~~~
        <div class="marquee horizontal inner">
            ~~~~~~~~~
        </div>
        <br/>
        ~~~~~
    </div>
</div>
```

```css
@keyframes marquee-vertical {
    0% { transform: translateY(0); }
    50% { transform: translateY(100%); }
    100% { transform: translateY(0); }
}

@keyframes marquee-horizontal {
    0% { transform: translateX(0); }
    50% { transform: translateX(100%); }
    100% { transform: translateX(0); }
}

.marquee.vertical {
    animation: marquee-vertical 5s linear infinite alternate;
}

.marquee.horizontal {
    animation: marquee-horizontal 5s linear infinite alternate;
}

.marquee.inner {
    animation-direction: reverse;
}
```

In this CSS version, you define keyframes for the two directions and apply them to the container elements, with the `inner` class elements moving in the opposite direction by setting `animation-direction: reverse;`. This method is much more consistent and reliable than using deprecated `<marquee>` tags.
